98 SECTION 3. Section 1 of chapter 175H of the General Laws, as so appearing, is hereby
99 amended by adding the following definitions:-
100 “Impermissible facility fee,” a facility fee, as defined in section 51L of chapter 111, that
101 is not charged, billed or collected in accordance with paragraphs (b) or (c) of said section 51L of
102 said chapter 111.
103 “Surprise bill,” a bill received by an insured for unforeseen out-of-network services, as
104 defined in section 30 of chapter 176O.
105 SECTION 4. Said chapter 175H of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022 Official
106 Edition, is hereby further amended by striking out in their entirety sections 5 and 6 and inserting
107 in place thereof the following sections:-
108 Section 5. The attorney general may conduct an investigation of an alleged violation of
109 this chapter and may commence a proceeding pursuant to section 4. Additionally, the attorney
110 general has the authority to initiate a civil action under this chapter. When the attorney general
111 has determined that a provider has violated this chapter, the attorney general shall notify the
112 department of public health, the department of mental health, the board of registration in
113 medicine or any other relevant licensing authorities, of that determination. Those licensing
114 authorities may, upon their own investigation or upon notification from the attorney general that
115 a provider licensed by that authority has violated this section, impose penalties for non-
116 compliance consistent with their authority to regulate those providers.
117 Section 6. A person who receives a health care benefit or payment from a health care
118 corporation or health care insurer or other person or entity, which such person knows that he or
119 she is not entitled to receive or be paid, or a person who knowingly presents or causes to be
6 of 10

120 presented with fraudulent intent a claim which contains a false statement, including but not
121 limited to a payment or false statement regarding an impermissible facility fee shall be liable to
122 the health care corporation or health care insurer or other person or entity for the full amount of
123 the benefit or payment made, and for reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, inclusive of costs of
124 investigation. A health care corporation or health care insurer or other injured person or entity
125 may bring a civil action under this chapter in the superior court department of the trial court.
126 Section 6A. A person who receives a health care benefit or payment from a health care
127 corporation or health care insurer or other person or entity shall not be permitted to forward a
128 surprise bill to a person covered under an insured health plan. A person who violates this section
129 shall be liable to the health care corporation or health care insurer or other person or entity for
130 penalties and for reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, inclusive of costs of investigation. A
131 health care corporation or health care insurer or other injured person or entity may bring a civil
132 action under this chapter in the superior court department of the trial court.
133 SECTION 5. Chapter 176J of the General Laws is hereby amended by inserting after
134 section 17 the following section:-
135 Section 18. Carriers shall reimburse evaluation and management services delivered by an
136 off-campus hospital outpatient department, clinic, ambulatory surgical center, or stand-alone
137 emergency department, and ambulatory services commonly provided in office-based settings,
138 including but not limited to laboratory tests, imaging, and diagnostic services, and clinician-
139 administered drugs that are identified by the health policy commission, as equivalent to the non-
140 facility rate in the Medicare physician fee schedule that applies to physician offices.
