141 SECTION 6. Chapter 176O of the General Laws is hereby amended by inserting after
142 section 30 the following section:-
143 Section 31. (a) As used in this section, “unforeseen out-of-network service” shall mean
144 the following: (1) health care services rendered by an out-of-network provider for emergency
145 medical conditions, including post-stabilization services resulting from an emergency medical
146 condition; (2) non-emergency health care services rendered by an out-of-network provider at an
147 in-network facility, including but not limited to: (i) services for emergency medicine,
148 anesthesiology, pathology, radiology, or neonatology, or services rendered by assistant surgeons,
149 hospitalists, and intensivists; (ii) health care services rendered by an out-of-network provider
150 without the insured’s advanced knowledge, pursuant to the requirements set forth in subsections
151 (b) through (e) of section 228 of chapter 111; (iii) health care services provided by an out-of-
152 network provider if there is no in-network provider who can furnish such health care service at
153 such facility; (iv) health care services rendered by an out-of-network provider, including an out-
154 of-network laboratory, radiologist, or pathologist, where the health care services were referred,
155 or an insured’s specimen was sent, by a participating provider to an out-of-network provider; or
156 (v) unforeseen health care services that arise at the time health care services are rendered that
157 must necessarily be rendered by an out-of-network provider; and (3) health care services
158 delivered by an ambulance service provider licensed by the department of public health pursuant
159 to section 6 of chapter 111C.
160 (b) An insured shall only be required to pay an out-of-network provider who renders an
161 unforeseen out-of-network service the applicable coinsurance, copayment, deductible or other
162 out-of-pocket expense that would be imposed if the service was rendered by a participating
163 provider. Payments made by an insured pursuant to this section shall count towards any in-
8 of 10

164 network deductible or out-of-pocket maximum pursuant to the terms and conditions of an
165 insured’s health benefit plan.
166 (c) A carrier shall reimburse an out-of-network provider who renders an unforeseen out-
167 of-network service to an insured at the carrier’s median contracted rate for that service in the
168 geographic region in the relevant market. Such payment shall constitute payment in full to the
169 out-of-network provider and the out-of-network provider shall not bill the insured for any
170 amount except for any in-network cost sharing amount owed for such service.
171 (d) With respect to an entity providing or administering a self-funded health benefit plan
172 governed by the provisions of the federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, 29
173 U.S.C. § 1001 et seq. and its plan members, this section shall only apply if the plan elects to be
174 subject to the provisions of this section. To elect to be subject to the provisions of this section,
175 the self-funded health benefit plan shall provide notice to the division on an annual basis, in a
176 form and manner prescribed by the division, attesting to the plan’s participation and agreeing to
177 be bound by the provisions of this section. The self-funded health benefit plan shall amend the
178 health benefit plan, coverage policies, contracts and any other plan documents to reflect that the
179 benefits of this section shall apply to the plan’s members.
180 (e) This section shall not be construed to require a carrier to cover health care services not
181 required by law or by the terms and conditions of an insured’s health benefit plan. Nothing in
182 this section shall require a carrier to pay for health care services delivered to an insured that are
183 not covered benefits under the terms of the insured’s health benefit plan.
184 (f) Nothing in this section shall require a carrier to pay for nonemergency services
185 delivered to an insured if the insured had a reasonable opportunity to choose to have the service
